metadata.name: Once and Future Cities #58
metadata.description:
When I was a kid I used to take apart broken electronic devices and look at the circuits, especially those with lots of good-sized components. As a scifi fan, I played with them imagining they were models of futuristic cities. For this piece I wanted to turn those memories of my childhood fantasies into glowing cyberpunk metropolises that resemble circuitry and are digital art made by computer circuits.

On the technical side, I used shaders to procedurally create the geometries and the textures. These geometries do not have vertex data like usual 3D, but are defined by mathematical functions, the so called "implicit surfaces". For each pixel a vector is constructed whose direction is used to make a simulated "scanning ray" that march step by step towards the scene, testing if it collides or not with any surface, and thus calculating the color that pixel should have. This technique is called raymarching and in this case the surface that defines the geometry is a height map.

For the procedural texture I used a formula that I discovered some years ago, a fractal of the kleinian family, in this case the square cousin version that produces patterns that look somewhat like circuits and that I have already used in other productions.

Finally there is the post processing shader, for which I developed a noisy bloom effect and a depth of field algorithm that receives from the main shader the distance from the camera for each pixel using the alpha channel.

The variations are achieved with the parameters sent to the shader and used by the hash functions that set the position and shape of the buildings, the different perspectives, the colors and patterns of the procedural textures, and the gradient of the sky.

Best viewed full screen. Also it will adapt to any aspect ratio.

In live mode:

Press 'S' to save a 3840x2160 image (16:9) 
Press 'W' to save a 3840x1080 image (32:9)

This project is GPU demanding and not intended to be run on mobile devices or low end hardware. Specially high res image generation, that is likely to fail on low end GPU's.

metadata.name: Scraps #28
metadata.description:
This generative art token is the second collaboration between artist Kristen Applegate and the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC. 

We share 33% of future royalties with the original minters in an effort to encourage the promotion of fxhash artists and raise awareness of generative art on the blockchain. We want this art to spread far and wide. Thank you for your support in helping us accomplish this goal.


Token Details:

Scraps
Collab by kmappleg8 x NFTMuseumSC
October 2022
fxhash Compliant NFT


Artist Bio:

kmappleg8 is an artist and assistant professor in the Department of Art + Design at Lander University in Greenwood, SC. She is new to coding and generative art but not to digital design. She eagerly awaits the time when her coding skills will enable her to bring more complex ideas to fruition. When not in the classroom or in front of her laptop, she can be found making pretty good ceramic work and mediocre flower beds.


Artist Statement

I like to encourage clay to look like other materials, such as food or fabric. For this project my black and white stoneware both agreed to appear as scraps of fabric hung on miniature hangers. Each scrap has a different personality. Some hang casually while others are tightly scrunched. These pieces are currently on display in an exhibition in conjunction with the 44th Annual Tri-State Sculptors Conference at Wofford College in Spartanburg, SC. The idea for the NFT came about from having to make a decision about how these scraps could be combined and displayed. Thanks to Robert at the NFT museum for expanding the possibilities.


Additional Credits and Attributions:

- Coded using p5js: https://p5js.org/


About the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC:

Established in October of 2021, the mission of the Non-Fungible Token Museum is to provide a physical and virtual space for NFT art education, collaboration and exhibition in an effort to help our communities benefit from emerging blockchain technologies. Learn more at www.NonFungibleTokenMuseum.org

metadata.name: Commune #50
metadata.description:
A minimalist composition with a nod towards architecture.

2932 bytes of Vanilla JS.

For more info, see article linked below: Me, Commune, Etc.

In live mode:
’S’ : save as svg (without grain)
‘P’ : save as png (3780x2673)

URL params in live mode:
‘g=n’ : no grain
‘g=w’ : wood grain
‘h=t’ : high resolution mode, 7560 × 5346 (Chrome only)

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save the png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: BRUTALIST MANIFESTO #5
metadata.description:
Discovered and brought into daylight from under gigantic concrete pylons of ancient digital monuments by brutologists. 

Written on multiple screens with blocks and bytes and bits in a language long forgotten.

Decyphering has already started for the sole purpose of understanding the roots of the new Brutalist Movement. 

These are the fragments of the BRUTALIST MANIFESTO.

///

Tech specs already decrypted from the fragments:

Randomized parameters
- 12 color palettes
- 5-8-10 rows
- 5-8-10 columns
- 0-8 blocks per glyphs
- 0-all special glyphs per row
- very rare occasion of a glitched glyph

Press 's' to download an image in 2k at any time of the generation.

///

Have fun decyphering!

☁︎

cloudnoise © 2022

///

Created with P5.js library.

metadata.name: Bifurcation Rains #8
metadata.description:
When you look at the cityscape outside the window through the glass with the raindrops, it always seems to be undecided about its choice of state and position in space. It flows and wriggles, becoming fluid, half-river, half-thought-out fantasy. 
Bifurcation diagrams are visually similar to these traces left by water on glass. We have tried to imagine a moving world, which right now is at a point of choice.

Made with love, AI and p5.js code
To save the image, press the 's' key. Enjoy!

October, 2022
Julia V & YulikolaY

metadata.name: Primordial #14
metadata.description:
Primordial is a study of abstract forms. The algorithm, written in p5.js and WebGL, utilizes domain warping to create twisted fields of color and then overlays thousands of tiny lines to provide depth and texture. The outputs are chaotic but not completely formless, like a swirling mass of plasma from the early universe, or a strange proto-life form suspended in prehistoric ooze.

CONTROLS:

1-9: Increase resolution and save image in PNG format

B: Toggle borders on/off

F: Fullscreen
P: Portrait
L: Landscape
S: Square

For third party license information, please see license.md

David Brice Allen
October 2022
